{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01R2Lm37xnf7DW1SEUBStzda","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me outline my proposed changes and write the improvement plan.\n\n**Failure 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" → ''**\n\nThe pre-merge correctly creates the full candidate. It passes hard filters. But embedding scoring kills it because ingredient words (Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce, Coriander) pull it toward HEADER_REFERENCE. The rawScore ends up below 0.08 threshold and no candidate survives.\n\nFix: Add a \"sole survivor\" / \"unambiguous pool\" fallback. If after threshold filtering, `selected` is empty, but there are candidates that passed hard filters, return the best one — especially if it's at position 0 or the pool is tiny. This is the simplest and most robust fix. \n\nThe hard filters are already doing their job by excluding ingredients and noise, so if a candidate made it through and nothing else survived the embedding threshold, it deserves a second chance.\n\n**Failure 2: \"Faszerowana papryka\" → 'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'**\n\nThe first-line protection at lines 468-479 requires both candidates in `selected`. But \"Faszerowana papryka\" is below threshold (threshold inflated by PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM's bonuses). \n\nFix: Move the first-line protection to BEFORE the threshold filter so it can rescue the correct candidate before embedding scoring inflates the competing option.\n\nI'm considering a two-part approach: always include position-0 candidates that pass hard filters in `selected` regardless of threshold, since recipe titles almost always appear first, and move first-line protection before the threshold calculation. But I need to be careful—position 0 could still be noise in edge cases, though the hard filters should catch most of that. The real issue for failure 2 is that the threshold calculation uses bonuses from the wrong candidate, so I should either exclude those bonuses when scoring non-ALL_CAPS candidates or compute the threshold before applying position-based boosts. The threshold is too aggressive and doesn't account for structural certainty. I need two fixes: first, add a position-0 safety net that force-includes any candidate at position 0 that passes hard filters if nothing else makes it through threshold filtering. Second, move the bilingual title protection to run before threshold calculation on the full scored list—if position 0 is mixed-case and there's exactly one ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2, remove that ALL_CAPS candidate before computing the threshold so its bonuses don't artificially inflate the cutoff.\n\nFor the ingredient-bearing titles issue, the position-0 fallback alone should handle it cleanly by ensuring we always have at least one unambiguous candidate from the full pool when threshold filtering leaves us empty.\n\nFor the bilingual pattern detection, I'll run the check on the pre-threshold scored array and use option (b)—force-including the position-0 candidate in the final selection regardless of threshold—since that integrates more smoothly with the existing logic.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1486,"cache_read_input_tokens":33966,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1486},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7bdf839d-85df-40e4-96e0-3a9dda0250b7","uuid":"ef296292-f1cb-49cc-af31-03e5712e1365"}
